article.headline: New York takes third place in East with win
article.linkText: Hammon's late scoring spree lifts Liberty
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Becky Hammon picked the right spot to push
her team to a third straight road victory.

Hammon scored 11 of her 13 points in the final 5 minutes,
leading the New York Liberty past the Minnesota Lynx 59-47 Sunday
night.

"I was just choosing my times and it happened to be at the end
of the game," Hammon said. "This was the fourth game in a row on
the road and we were tired. I think we just had to fight through
it."

Elena Baranova added 12 points and Crystal Robinson 11 for the
Liberty, who finished their road trip 3-1 and took over sole
possession of third place in the Eastern Conference. New York
(11-9) has won five straight in Minnesota.

"We just talked about perseverence," head coach Pat Coyle said
after watching her team play sluggishly in the first half. "The
second half was much better basketball."

Nicole Ohlde scored 17 points for the Lynx (11-10), who fell
into fifth place in the Western Conference. Vanessa Hayden added
13, but leading scorer Katie Smith was held to just five points on
2-of-12 shooting.

Minnesota, which was 0-for-13 on 3-pointers, lost for just the
third time in 11 home games.

"You'd love to give credit to their defense, but I can't say it
was all their defense," head coach Suzie McConnell Serio said.
"We missed a lot of open shots."

"Tonight would have been a big win for us and we let it slip
away," she added.

Neither team could gain control until the Liberty went on a 7-2
run, capped by Wauters' jump hook, to grab a 42-35 advantage with
7:18 left. New York used a 9-2 run, capped by Hammon's 3-pointer,
to extend the lead to 51-41 with 2:10 left, and the Lynx didn't get
closer than eight points the rest of the way.

"I think that shot just broke their back," Coyle said of
Hammon's 3-pointer. "She's played a lot of minutes on this trip,
but she doesn't care how tired she is."

Both teams shot poorly in the first half. Minnesota was 27
percent from the field, New York shot 38 percent. The game was tied
five times and the lead changed 10 times before the Liberty went
into the break ahead 20-18 during the lowest scoring first half for
both teams.

Lynx forward Svetlana Abrosimova started after missing two games
with back spasms. She scored four points on 2-of-7 shooting.

Minnesota announced guard Tynesha Lewis has been signed for the
remainder of the season.
